Bayes in Practice

José Iglesias 2013

Month At Bats H AVG
April 20 9 .450

What is your prediction for his average in October?

Note: No one has finished a season batting .400 since Ted Williams in 1941!

Distribution of AVG

This is for all players (>500 AB) 2010, 2011, 2012

Average is .275 and SD is 0.027

José Iglesias’ April batting average

  • Should we trade him?

  • What is the SE of our estimate?

  • .450(1−.450)20‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾‾√=.111.450(1−.450)20=.111

  • Confidence interval?

  • .450-.222 to .450+.222 = .228 to .672

Hierarchichal Model

Pick a random player, then what is their batting average

θY|θ∼∼N(μ,τ2) is called a priorN(θ,σ2) is called a sampling distributionθ∼N(μ,τ2) is called a priorY|θ∼N(θ,σ2) is called a sampling distribution

Two levels of variability:

  • Player to player variability
  • Variability due to luck when batting

Hierarchichal Model

θY|θ∼∼N(μ,τ2) is called a priorN(θ,σ2) is called a sampling distributionθ∼N(μ,τ2) is called a priorY|θ∼N(θ,σ2) is called a sampling distribution

  • θθ is our players “intrinsic” average value
  • μμ is the average of all players
  • ττ is the SD of all players
  • YY is the observed average
  • σσ is the variability due to luck at each AB

Hierarchichal Model

Here are the equations with our data

θY|θ∼∼N(.275,.0272)N(θ,.1102)θ∼N(.275,.0272)Y|θ∼N(θ,.1102)

Posterior Distribution

The continuous version of Bayes rule can be used here

fθ|Y(θ|Y)==fY|θ(Y|θ)fθ(θ)fY(Y)fY|θ(Y|θ)fθ(θ)∫θfY|θ(Y|θ)fθ(θ)fθ|Y(θ|Y)=fY|θ(Y|θ)fθ(θ)fY(Y)=fY|θ(Y|θ)fθ(θ)∫θfY|θ(Y|θ)fθ(θ)

We are particularly interested in the θθ that maximizes fθ|Y(θ|Y)fθ|Y(θ|Y).

In our case, these can be shown to be normal so we want the average E(θ|y)E(θ|y)

Posterior Distribution

We can show the average of this distribution is the following:

E(θ|y)B===Bμ+(1−B)Yμ+(1−B)(Y−μ)σ2σ2+τ2E(θ|y)=Bμ+(1−B)Y=μ+(1−B)(Y−μ)B=σ2σ2+τ2

Posterior Distribution

In the case of José Iglesias, we have:

E(θ|Y=.450)BE(θ|Y=450)===≈B×.275+(1−B)×.450.275+(1−B)(.450−.260).1102.1102+.0272=0.943.285E(θ|Y=.450)=B×.275+(1−B)×.450=.275+(1−B)(.450−.260)B=.1102.1102+.0272=0.943E(θ|Y=450)≈.285

Posterior Distribution

The variance can be shown to be:

var(θ|y)=11/σ2+1/τ2=11/.1102+1/.0272var(θ|y)=11/σ2+1/τ2=11/.1102+1/.0272

In our example the SD is 0.026
